00:33:46,738 --> 00:33:47,618
Mr. Superintendent.

464
00:33:47,838 --> 00:33:56,140
Madam Mayor and members of the committee, we're calling on our Deputy Superintendent to take you through the report on district and school 2015 accountability levels.

465
00:33:56,921 --> 00:33:58,621
It's a very complex area.

466
00:33:58,881 --> 00:34:02,582
A lot is changing and we want to make sure you're fully aware.

467
00:34:04,140 --> 00:34:05,621
Yes, the word is complex.

468
00:34:05,681 --> 00:34:26,069
If you had a chance to look through some of the data and the reports attached, we have been working with this, a team of us, trying to wrap our arms around the whole process and make some sense out of all of the data that we're given, because oftentimes it's contradictory, as I will be pointing out to you in some of the sheets that are attached.

469
00:34:27,209 --> 00:34:28,610
We put together this report.

470
00:34:28,630 --> 00:34:30,011
It has many purposes.

471
00:34:31,933 --> 00:34:40,197
Department of Elementary and Secondary Education has publicly released their 2015 accountability determination.

472
00:34:40,918 --> 00:34:45,220
All schools are given a determination as well as all school districts.

473
00:34:46,781 --> 00:35:00,968
The purpose of this report is to explain to you what the accountability system is made up of and the various changes because even though this is a system that we were held to a target after four years,

474
00:35:01,542 --> 00:35:09,167
Throughout the system, throughout the years, there have been changes and that really is very concerning as we move forward.

475
00:35:10,168 --> 00:35:16,572
We also want to report to you on Medford's accountability status of all of the schools and the district.

476
00:35:17,612 --> 00:35:24,357
And then we want to interpret, to the best of our ability, the findings based on the data we have received.

477
00:35:24,917 --> 00:35:29,140
And so again, we've been working with many of our administrators on all of this.

478
00:35:31,060 --> 00:35:32,900
First of all, the accountability system.

479
00:35:34,581 --> 00:35:45,703
In 2011, Massachusetts applied for and was allowed a waiver of exemption from the provision of the federal law, No Child Left Behind.

480
00:35:46,583 --> 00:35:52,624
This particular law required that all students reach proficiency levels by the school year 2013-2014.

481
00:35:52,644 --> 00:35:55,024
Massachusetts determined the level of proficiency

482
00:35:59,564 --> 00:36:01,405
as the proficiency level of MCAS.

483
00:36:02,626 --> 00:36:11,011
Every year, since that accountability system started, the bar would go higher because, again, the goal was for everyone to be at least 240 by 2014.

484
00:36:11,572 --> 00:36:25,080
And as that date came closer and closer and school districts throughout the country were not making this benchmark, that's why the waiver was put into effect as an offering.

485
00:36:25,901 --> 00:36:27,462
So Massachusetts, again,

486
00:36:28,590 --> 00:36:35,752
had to identify an alternative accountability system, and that had to be subject to the approval of the federal government.

487
00:36:36,332 --> 00:36:53,817
So they did, we did, and the new accountability system, rather than having all students reach proficiency by a certain year, was to have all students, well, have all schools reduce what was called the proficiency gap among the different subgroups.

488
00:36:54,857 --> 00:36:58,318
The gap was supposed to be, is supposed to be reduced by half

489
00:36:58,847 --> 00:36:59,928
by the year 2017.

490
00:37:01,028 --> 00:37:08,973
So again, as we move closer and closer to 2017, the expectation bar is higher and higher in closing that gap.

491
00:37:11,555 --> 00:37:20,461
We are now on an annual basis held to this new system, which rates schools and districts from levels one to five.

492
00:37:20,621 --> 00:37:25,384
One being the best, five is not where you want to be because that's when the state comes in and intervenes.

493
00:37:27,335 --> 00:37:39,524
Although we get individual accountability ratings for each of our schools, the rating of the school district can be no higher than the rating of the lowest performing school.

494
00:37:40,244 --> 00:37:46,809
Okay, again, this is rather punitive in nature and something that we're held to.

495
00:37:47,749 --> 00:37:55,335
Accountability ratings are based on a statistic called the PPI, the Progress and Performance Index.

496
00:37:55,999 --> 00:37:59,981
which is a complex formula which is very hard to decipher.

497
00:38:00,141 --> 00:38:14,990
And DESE simply has said to us it's based on seven indicators that include performance on MCAS over a four-year period, student growth percentiles, science performance, and then other indicators.

498
00:38:15,050 --> 00:38:19,592
Now, what those other indicators are, we have not been able to get clarity around that.

499
00:38:20,813 --> 00:38:24,735
Each year, the target number for closing the gap among the subgroups

500
00:38:25,152 --> 00:38:30,515
increases since the goal of closing the gap by half is 2017.

501
00:38:31,136 --> 00:38:36,239
This year, the target number, and I'm not sure how they arrived at that, was the number 75.

502
00:38:36,359 --> 00:38:43,784
OK, so if you're going to meet your target, you had to hit that with all of your subgroups and, again, as an aggregate in the school.

503
00:38:46,125 --> 00:38:54,551
This year, for the first time, school districts this past year in the Commonwealth were allowed to have students take either MCAS or PAR.

504
00:38:55,743 --> 00:39:00,405
Those districts that opted for PARCC were held harmless in accountability ratings.

505
00:39:01,285 --> 00:39:07,268
Despite being held harmless, they were designated ratings along with the districts that took MCAS.

506
00:39:08,248 --> 00:39:16,231
Logically, there were questions related to using the same rating system for two very different assessment instruments.

507
00:39:17,612 --> 00:39:23,474
DESE's answer to this is that they have developed a formula, a special formula,

508
00:39:24,073 --> 00:39:26,374
called the equi-percentile linking.

509
00:39:30,194 --> 00:39:35,136
To date, we do not have the magical ingredients for this formula.

510
00:39:35,596 --> 00:39:45,138
And we remain very skeptical, since according to psychometrics, if you do a valid longitudinal comparison, all the variables have to stay constant.

511
00:39:45,478 --> 00:39:47,579
You can't keep changing things from year to year.

512
00:39:47,979 --> 00:39:49,519
And that's what they've been doing with this.

513
00:39:49,579 --> 00:39:53,260
So again, it doesn't make sense from a perspective of assessment.

514
00:39:54,350 --> 00:39:54,730
logic.

515
00:39:56,751 --> 00:40:08,774
Again, how school districts can be rated on the same scale using two very different testing systems remains to us perplexing and we don't have a good answer as to how they are equating the two.

516
00:40:10,334 --> 00:40:21,837
While the final goal for performance is based upon growth over four years, DESE has made several changes related to this year's reports and plans for additional changes for 2016.

517
00:40:23,945 --> 00:40:25,905
These changes include the following.

518
00:40:27,346 --> 00:40:32,087
They have created a brand new subgroup called the Economically Disadvantaged.

519
00:40:32,687 --> 00:40:44,249
This subgroup replaces the former low-income subgroup, which was reported through 2014 and was determined based on student eligibility for free and reduced lunch.

520
00:40:45,329 --> 00:40:52,671
The new Economically Disadvantaged group only includes students who participate in one or more of the state

521
00:40:53,176 --> 00:41:05,668
administered programs such as the Supplemental Nutrition Assistant Program, Transitional Assistance for Families and Dependent Children, DCF Foster Care Program, and MassHealth.

522
00:41:06,008 --> 00:41:07,590
So those youngsters are in that subgroup.

523
00:41:07,850 --> 00:41:10,532
And I will add that a youngster can be in multiple subgroups.

524
00:41:11,393 --> 00:41:17,579
They could be in the economically disadvantaged, they could be in the special education, they could be in the ELL.

525
00:41:19,790 --> 00:41:21,931
Again, one student can be counted.

526
00:41:21,951 --> 00:41:23,692
The score can be counted multiple times.

527
00:41:24,212 --> 00:41:25,093
So that was one change.

528
00:41:25,113 --> 00:41:26,013
They changed the subgroup.

529
00:41:26,413 --> 00:41:30,235
So now we get reported out in a subgroup that didn't exist in a previous year.

530
00:41:31,215 --> 00:41:39,839
Secondly, and this is very troubling to me, they're changing the number of students required in a subgroup to report out.

531
00:41:40,440 --> 00:41:41,480
It used to be 40.

532
00:41:41,540 --> 00:41:42,601
You would not get a report.

533
00:41:42,621 --> 00:41:44,622
Let's say you had a subgroup ELL students.

534
00:41:45,182 --> 00:41:47,583
Unless you had 40 ELL students in that school,

535
00:41:48,320 --> 00:41:50,881
you would not have a report on how those students did.

536
00:41:51,362 --> 00:41:56,585
And that's logical, too, because the smaller the sample, the more skewed the results are going to be.

537
00:41:56,665 --> 00:42:01,927
If you have a sample of 40 kids, you have a pretty broad scope of students that are tested.

538
00:42:03,208 --> 00:42:13,534
So what we learned over our discussions with DESE the past few weeks is that the minimum group for accountability determination in 2014 was moved to 30.

539
00:42:16,916 --> 00:42:24,041
Even more troubling, 2015, it was 25, and lo and behold, they told us next year it's going to be 20.

540
00:42:25,061 --> 00:42:33,827
This causes some real problems when you're really analyzing data, because the groups that we have 20 in now, we have no reporting out this year.

541
00:42:34,267 --> 00:42:39,751
Unless we go back individual student by student, we don't know what that group is doing.

542
00:42:39,791 --> 00:42:42,553
But next year, that might be reported out to us.

543
00:42:43,213 --> 00:42:45,675
So again, changing these numbers is

544
00:42:46,337 --> 00:42:51,720
very difficult to justify, and it's very problematic to analyze.

545
00:42:53,982 --> 00:43:04,688
The other interesting thing was this year, the accountability system, the PPI, was awarding bonus points.

546
00:43:05,429 --> 00:43:07,390
So we asked, how do you get bonus points?

547
00:43:07,490 --> 00:43:10,672
Because bonus points are really very valuable and very important to us.

548
00:43:11,532 --> 00:43:14,014
And we were told that bonus points are only given

549
00:43:14,757 --> 00:43:24,625
when you move 10% of your students from warning slash failing to needs improvement or 10% of your students from proficient to advanced.

550
00:43:25,245 --> 00:43:32,431
And as we sat in that meeting with our representative from DSAC, we were just aghast because we said, you mean we get nothing?

551
00:43:33,027 --> 00:43:40,754
from moving students from Needs Improvement to Proficient, which is the whole goal of the system, as long as we have been doing this.

552
00:43:41,515 --> 00:43:48,061
We have moved a lot of students out of Need Improvement to Proficient, and we get nothing in terms of bonus points.

553
00:43:48,581 --> 00:43:50,703
And if you look at it numerically, think about it.

554
00:43:51,123 --> 00:43:59,411
If you have 10 students in the winning category, and you have to move 10% out, and that's one kid, you get bonus points for moving one student up.

555
00:44:00,016 --> 00:44:04,737
If you have a hundred students that needs improvement and you get them all to proficient, you get nothing.

556
00:44:05,818 --> 00:44:06,458
Really fair.

557
00:44:07,038 --> 00:44:07,978
It makes a lot of sense.

558
00:44:08,599 --> 00:44:09,679
Makes no sense.

559
00:44:10,039 --> 00:44:10,439
I'm sorry.

560
00:44:10,799 --> 00:44:16,141
I've been in this business so long that it gets, I guess, more and more perplexing to me.

561
00:44:17,401 --> 00:44:26,684
Okay, in terms of Medfit's accountability rating, we have some success stories and we have one problematic area that we're still working through.

562
00:44:27,677 --> 00:44:32,260
The Bedford High School, Bedford Vocational School are both level one, that's the best you can be.

563
00:44:32,720 --> 00:44:33,821
That's a good place to be.

564
00:44:34,682 --> 00:44:40,365
Level two, all of our other schools, our middle schools, our elementary schools are level two.

565
00:44:40,866 --> 00:44:46,549
The Roberts is level three, and I'll go into some of the reasons we can glean for that happening.

566
00:44:47,930 --> 00:44:50,892
Unfortunately, as the system is designed,

567
00:44:52,885 --> 00:44:56,466
Your rating is only good as a district as your lowest performing school.

568
00:44:56,987 --> 00:44:58,627
So you're rated, we're rated level three.

569
00:44:59,368 --> 00:45:06,190
And again, that gives you publicly no credit for all the good things that are happening at all of the schools, including the Roberts.

570
00:45:06,571 --> 00:45:10,192
Because again, we are looking at the Roberts data and we're questioning some of that too.

571
00:45:10,652 --> 00:45:13,673
They were basically one point away from making level two.

572
00:45:14,274 --> 00:45:21,457
And my question, because I always cut right to the heart of things is, what did we have to do to get that one point to get to the 21 from 20?

573
00:45:22,782 --> 00:45:24,202
And no one can give me an answer.

574
00:45:24,222 --> 00:45:27,683
They just give me more charts and more numbers and more statistics.

575
00:45:27,763 --> 00:45:32,745
So again, we're not getting great answers as we go through this, and we're trying to do our best.

576
00:45:33,045 --> 00:45:34,825
We don't want that school to be level three.

577
00:45:34,845 --> 00:45:36,305
We don't want the district to be level three.

578
00:45:36,706 --> 00:45:40,947
But you need to tell me why I'm there in order to tell me what I need to do to get out of that.

579
00:45:41,347 --> 00:45:43,367
And that's where we're kind of stuck at this point.

580
00:45:43,767 --> 00:45:46,208
We're getting glimmers of information here.

581
00:45:48,629 --> 00:45:50,229
So the interpretation of the data.

582
00:45:51,225 --> 00:45:58,171
We've had our administrative team over the past two weeks looking at this, asking questions, having DSAC people in.

583
00:46:01,333 --> 00:46:09,680
And if you look at the district data and the Roberts data too, you can see that we have made gains in both ELA and mathematics.

584
00:46:11,121 --> 00:46:17,867
Extra credit has been in high growth, has been given for our ELL performance on the access test.

585
00:46:18,705 --> 00:46:29,210
This to me, again, is another perplexing piece, because we're told that one of the reasons why the Roberts did not make their goal is because of the subgroup ELL.

586
00:46:29,950 --> 00:46:33,792
Yet, we're getting bonus points for their performance on access.

587
00:46:34,952 --> 00:46:35,232
Okay?

588
00:46:35,352 --> 00:46:37,854
I'm a very logical person, and that's illogical to me.

589
00:46:37,974 --> 00:46:40,975
So, again, these are some of the things we're struggling with.

590
00:46:42,208 --> 00:46:55,493
Our analysis of our overall student growth percentiles show that we are in the moderate to high range for all groups across all schools, and that's a 40 to 60 numerical figure, and we're well within that and even above it.

591
00:46:56,833 --> 00:47:02,215
As a level three district now, we are required to work with the District School Assistance Center, DSAC.

592
00:47:03,196 --> 00:47:09,718
The leadership team met with our DSAC coordinator, Mary Ann Jackman, and the regional data specialist, Hillary

593
00:47:10,177 --> 00:47:19,603
Bresnahan on Friday, January 22nd, and we posed several questions about the data that, again, to date, remain unanswered to a certain extent.

594
00:47:19,623 --> 00:47:24,046
They've been coming back with some answers, but not all of the answers that we asked for.

595
00:47:25,347 --> 00:47:36,414
We are really concerned, I'm concerned, about a system that is intended to measure progress over time whose tools for that exact measurement vary from year to year.

596
00:47:37,667 --> 00:47:41,150
We liken the process to that of trying to hit a moving target.

597
00:47:42,070 --> 00:47:58,962
We have brought our concerns to the Massachusetts Association of School Superintendents, who has responded to the superintendent that MedFit, with its diligence in examining the data, has brought to light aspects of the system unknown to most districts.

598
00:47:59,663 --> 00:48:06,508
We will continue to challenge what we feel is a system that works against the best interests of schools and our students.

599
00:48:08,240 --> 00:48:17,227
One of our goals as a school district, with or without an accountability system, has always been focused on improving student academic achievement.

600
00:48:18,048 --> 00:48:23,772
We feel that we have made significant progress in moving our students to higher levels of performance.

601
00:48:24,673 --> 00:48:34,320
Our student growth percentiles, as I mentioned before, are strong, and we continue to move students in large numbers into the proficiency category.

602
00:48:35,261 --> 00:48:44,086
While we recognize that there are still areas of improvement, we are focused on making sure that the data we use to make these improvements is sound.

603
00:48:45,087 --> 00:48:54,253
At this time, we have unanswered questions on how the state has interpreted results, not only for Medford, but also for all districts in the Commonwealth.

604
00:48:54,753 --> 00:49:01,317
We will continue to remain vigilant about the rating process and advocate for all of our students.

605
00:49:02,758 --> 00:49:04,319
I attach to the report

606
00:49:05,420 --> 00:49:12,944
just an understanding of the accountability system, just so you can get to see how they started in 2011.

