1196
01:34:06,162 --> 01:34:09,263
Report on Minuteman Regional Technical High School, Mr. Superintendent.

1197
01:34:09,283 --> 01:34:17,486
Madam Mayor, Minuteman's another example of something that we've worked with for a number of years.

1198
01:34:17,506 --> 01:34:21,907
And we've put a lot of money into Minuteman.

1199
01:34:22,608 --> 01:34:27,609
And to some degree, part of it was because our vocational school wasn't everything it needed to be.

1200
01:34:28,350 --> 01:34:30,951
But our vocational school is rising and done very, very well.

1201
01:34:33,274 --> 01:34:45,259
We've got a lot of other options in our collaborations with Cambridge and Somerville and Waltham that enable us to do some things that will help us keep our students home and keep our dollars home.

1202
01:34:46,340 --> 01:34:52,082
Minuteman Regional Technical High School currently serves 673 students from many different communities.

1203
01:34:52,522 --> 01:34:57,864
There are 16 member towns who enroll 396 students, and 277 students come from non-member towns, like Medford.

1204
01:35:03,058 --> 01:35:09,102
When Minuteman was originally built in Lexington in 1975, it projected serving almost 1,000 students.

1205
01:35:09,762 --> 01:35:13,265
The history of Minuteman enrollments tells us it was a very unrealistic projection.

1206
01:35:13,845 --> 01:35:26,453
Ron Fitzgerald, who at one time was the superintendent of Minuteman, told Commissioner Dave Driscoll at the time that he would always need at least 100 students from outside the district each year, each freshman class, to reach that goal.

1207
01:35:27,013 --> 01:35:28,414
And even with that, he didn't reach the goal.

1208
01:35:31,036 --> 01:35:32,597
The following is the current enrollment

1209
01:35:34,939 --> 01:35:35,860
from member towns.

1210
01:35:35,960 --> 01:35:43,102
You can see that, I'm not going to read it for you, but you can see some of the towns are very small, like Wayland 2 and West End 5 and so on and so forth.

1211
01:35:44,322 --> 01:35:51,685
And the big ones are Arlington, Lexington, Lancaster, Belmont to some degree, okay, Acton.

1212
01:35:52,885 --> 01:35:57,587
But they're made up of 16 towns and not many of them, you know, send a lot of Doversons to.

1213
01:35:58,887 --> 01:36:00,228
Seven of the member towns

1214
01:36:01,055 --> 01:36:05,758
are actively considering withdrawal from the regional district under a one-time option.

1215
01:36:06,819 --> 01:36:09,801
Normally, withdrawal would require a unanimous vote of all members.

1216
01:36:10,582 --> 01:36:13,684
The seven communities would decrease current enrollment by 57 students.

1217
01:36:13,704 --> 01:36:18,167
They include Boxboro, Carlisle, Dover, Lincoln, Sudbury, Wayland, and Weston.

1218
01:36:18,187 --> 01:36:20,569
Those are the ones who are actively voting.

1219
01:36:21,189 --> 01:36:26,713
Minuteman realized that it couldn't get 16 communities to vote for a revised regional agreement and for a new school.

1220
01:36:28,352 --> 01:36:35,396
So as a result, the school committee came up with a plan to allow communities to leave on a one-time option if they would approve the revised regional agreement.

1221
01:36:36,317 --> 01:36:37,297
This is what you've got here.

1222
01:36:38,318 --> 01:36:44,221
Seven communities can only leave if they approve the new regional agreement, which would diminish their voting capacity if they were to stay.

1223
01:36:45,002 --> 01:36:53,206
So if they stay, communities that send fewer kids would have almost proportionate voting, less power.

1224
01:36:53,226 --> 01:36:55,308
So instead of having a 1-0 vote, they might have a 0.5 vote.

1225
01:36:56,897 --> 01:36:58,658
OK, compared to communities that send a lot more.

1226
01:36:59,939 --> 01:37:08,665
The Minuteman School Committee devised this one, too, because with seven communities in opposition, there would be no constructive way to gain sufficient town meeting support across the region.

1227
01:37:09,446 --> 01:37:15,831
Seven projected leaving districts recognized they stay there for a pupil cost would be extraordinary for a limited number of students.

1228
01:37:16,291 --> 01:37:17,812
And the new building was constructive.

1229
01:37:18,512 --> 01:37:20,694
And the projected capital debt was apportioned.

1230
01:37:21,154 --> 01:37:23,396
For example, Weston would pay approximately $49,000 per student.

1231
01:37:23,436 --> 01:37:24,317
Good Harvard for that.

1232
01:37:27,157 --> 01:37:30,878
Plus a special needs cost assessment.

1233
01:37:32,679 --> 01:37:38,120
Minuteman is the most expensive vocational school in the state, with the exception of the agricultural schools.

1234
01:37:38,921 --> 01:37:40,021
And that's an under the instance.

1235
01:37:40,101 --> 01:37:41,561
Some of the agricultural schools are pretty good.

1236
01:37:42,422 --> 01:37:47,383
As previously stated, non-member cities and towns currently provide 277 students as follows.

1237
01:37:47,803 --> 01:37:52,445
Boston since 25, Medford since 34, Waltham 44, Watertown 66, and others about 109.

1238
01:37:58,612 --> 01:38:06,617
Next year, Medford will have 17 seniors graduating this year, and we'll have 17 students remaining there, and they can't take ninth graders.

1239
01:38:07,737 --> 01:38:14,461
The current base tuition for our district students is $17,005, plus $4,500 in special needs services required.

1240
01:38:14,961 --> 01:38:18,063
The rate is set by the commissioner, and that rate's coming down based on agreement.

1241
01:38:20,145 --> 01:38:25,889
Minute Man has the MSBA tentative go-ahead to build a new school in Lincoln for 628 students.

1242
01:38:25,949 --> 01:38:29,151
I have no idea how they're going to get 628 students there.

1243
01:38:30,032 --> 01:38:34,054
The towns that remain in the district must approve bonding for $144.9 million plus interest on a 30-year period, meaning $300 million.

1244
01:38:34,094 --> 01:38:36,676
State funding is projected to be $45,206,061 for the proposed 257,745 square foot school.

1245
01:38:51,835 --> 01:38:54,656
Okay?

1246
01:38:54,696 --> 01:39:09,323
Now, that 45,000 belies the reimbursement rate that's being advertised at 42, 43, 44%, because it's really only 32% of the actual cost, because not all costs that Minuteman is proposing are eligible for reimbursement.

1247
01:39:10,964 --> 01:39:12,124
It'll come out in the town meetings.

1248
01:39:13,045 --> 01:39:16,686
If the project goes forward, the school is expected to be open for the fall of 2019.

1249
01:39:16,726 --> 01:39:17,267
Most estimates are 2020.

1250
01:39:20,875 --> 01:39:21,715
take a little bit longer.

1251
01:39:22,556 --> 01:39:27,278
There are many non-financial contingencies to be worked out before construction can take place on the Lincoln site.

1252
01:39:27,698 --> 01:39:29,979
For example, wetlands, EPA.

1253
01:39:30,880 --> 01:39:40,684
Secondly, Lincoln is asking for mitigation for the use of their land, police and fire and other considerations yet to be decided by the Minuteman School Committee and others.

1254
01:39:41,145 --> 01:39:46,507
So we're not clear as to how that's going to play out and how that might delay or not delay what's going on.

1255
01:39:47,007 --> 01:39:48,308
So let's look at the Medford impact.

1256
01:39:50,328 --> 01:39:52,130
Currently, we have 34 students at Minutemen.

1257
01:39:52,230 --> 01:39:57,594
This year, 17 seniors will graduate, and no ninth graders can go there under the new state regulations.

1258
01:39:58,295 --> 01:40:01,978
Also, the expansion and development of our vocational program will keep future students home.

1259
01:40:02,839 --> 01:40:04,760
Three years ago, we had 50 students at Minutemen.

1260
01:40:05,381 --> 01:40:11,166
We also had cooperative agreements with neighboring districts in Cambridge, Somerville, Waltham, and Boston through our Solve Collaborative.

1261
01:40:11,906 --> 01:40:18,332
The reduction of our enrollment at Minutemen will enable us to save significant funding, which can be reinvested in our own school system.

1262
01:40:18,652 --> 01:40:23,473
in our own vocational school or other concerns that you would find to be priority.

1263
01:40:24,013 --> 01:40:36,077
The collaboration between the high school and the vocational school is also a major achievement, since it will enhance college prospects for our vocational students and provide occupational skill training options for high school students at a reasonable cost.

1264
01:40:36,897 --> 01:40:38,917
So this is what's going on right now.

1265
01:40:39,438 --> 01:40:42,458
Town meeting should take place somewhere before March 1st.

1266
01:40:43,179 --> 01:40:47,960
We'll begin to see what takes place and what moves forward, but it's clear

1267
01:40:49,418 --> 01:40:51,760
that we are moving away from Minuteman.

1268
01:40:52,821 --> 01:40:54,722
Minuteman has to solve its own issues.

1269
01:40:55,783 --> 01:41:01,087
Right now, financial, building, all those kinds of things, and there's a lot of disagreement among the towns.

1270
01:41:02,408 --> 01:41:03,829
That doesn't mean they won't build a school.

1271
01:41:04,929 --> 01:41:17,939
It just simply means I don't know how they're going to get 628 students when the Metro Vocational School and Waltham and other places are building and expanding their own programs so that, Somerville, so that

1272
01:41:18,747 --> 01:41:19,547
The kids are going to stay home.

1273
01:41:21,488 --> 01:41:22,409
Happy to take any questions.

1274
01:41:23,449 --> 01:41:25,630
Could I ask just one question from the chair?

1275
01:41:25,650 --> 01:41:25,730
Sure.

1276
01:41:25,870 --> 01:41:31,833
Lincoln is willing to host a new Minuteman Regional High School and they want to withdraw from the region?

1277
